From the highly acclaimed to the much-maligned: recent blu-ray acquisitions. üíô
At least one of these films is not as good as everyone makes it out to be, and some are better than everyone would have you think.
Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse (2018) is a thing of beauty, honouring the original character in so many ways while creating something new and fresh. It has heart aplenty, and its animation makes the screen come alive.
Aquaman (2018) is dumbish fun - but it‚Äôs so much fun, and it‚Äôs stunning to look at. Rewatch and tell me if some of those shots aren‚Äôt pure works of art. It‚Äôs closer to Guardians of the Galaxy and Black Panther than it is to the previous DC films. But I‚Äôm not complaining because those underwater effects look amazing, the synth soundtrack gives it a retro feel, and we get to see Dolph Lundgren, Willem Dafoe, Patrick Wilson and others being awesome under the sea. Oh yeah, Jason Momoa too.
Black Panther (2018) is good but a bit meh overall and too long. I love the strong female characters and Michael B. Jordan, and the world they inhabit. A lot of care and effort has gone into creating that world, which is kind of like Earth‚Äôs version of Asgard. It deserved a nomination for Best Picture at the Oscars no more than Aquaman did, IMO.
Daredevil (2003) is nowhere near as bad as everyone makes out. It has a misstep here or there but doesn‚Äôt deserve the hate. I feel sorry for Ben Affleck who has weathered the storms of failed superheroes less successfully than Ryan Reynolds. Also, this disc has an outstanding series of interviews with the writers and artists behind the Daredevil comics. Worth revisiting.

This is only the beginning of the song ‚ù£Ô∏è This video for my new song The Sun in My Universe features art from my earlier film series. It was an beautiful emotional process looking through these series and selecting a few favorite pieces. I poured my entire heart into each of these series. The memories associated with the times I worked hard on creating an homage to all these amazing films and directors are intricately woven into the art. The films featured are Experiment in Terror ( directed by Blake Edwards), Blade Runner (directed by Ridley Scott), Rear Window (directed by Alfred Hitchcock), Pulp Fiction (directed by Quentin Tarantino) Star Wars (directed by George Lucas), True Romance (directed by Tony Scott ), Blue Velvet (directed by David Lynch) Serenity (directed by Joss Whedon), & Casa Blanca (directed by Michael Curtiz) all my love and respect to all these directors. üíïüôèüíïüíïüíï check out Ilsa Kanto creations on YouTube. This 1945 Canadian paperback edition has a unique history. 
Published by Superior / Duchess Printing & Publishing in 1945, they erroneously issued the title as by John W. Campbell Jr., when in fact it is by legendary golden-era pulp writer Ray Cummings! 
To top off that idiocy, some genius stole or repurposed the cover art from the May 1941 edition of POPULAR MECHANICS magazine for this science fiction paperback (swipe left to compare the images). The novel originated in the pulp magazine ASTOUNDING STORIES OF SUPER-SCIENCE (1930: March, April, May, June) in four installments. 
Twelve years later, it was reprinted, in full, in the pulp magazine SCIENCE FICTION QUARTERLY (1942 Fall). Many websites ignorantly plagiarize each other and state it was first published in 1931. Morons! 1931 was actually the year it was bound as a hardcover by A. C. McClurg.

In 1958, ACE BOOKS released the first mass-market paperback edition. 
In the last 25 years, it has fallen into public domain and shitty Print on Demand editions readily abound. Don't buy from these cretins. Buy a vintage copy to read.

Once he composed himself somewhat, he found out from the neighbours that they reported the murder to the police confirming that his father could be the only person behind it as the saw him leave the house bloody "But what will you do Zach?" When asked he just shrugged "I don't know, but I know it ain't gonna be anything good..." then proceeded to leave back to his home still shaken and shocked, all he had was gone, he had nothing more to lose. 
All Zach had in thought was revenge it consumed him like a vile plague that he couldn't clear from his mind, meanwhile police were clearing the bodies of his loved one's confirming the crime mostly from fingerprints on left around weaponary, a very sloppy way of doing it so they went to look for John, Zach's father.

Nightfall eventually came and Zach had spent hours at home thinking over what had happened, had his father been caught yet? Should he go for him? Would it be worth it? It was alot to take in all at once he was well and truly alone.

He later found out his father was taken into custody for the murders, drug possession and drink driving it did anger him but also made him relieve that the monster behind the end of all that held him together was gone, he sat alone in tears as he just wished he could have his family back.

A year later [Age 19] Zach took up street fighting in the gritty streets and backalleys of Gotham going by the nickname "Dev" simply because most people that either faught or came to see him fight thought he was just pure evil, he needed money to live and he didn't care how or who he had go through to earn top pay.

It was the only way he could vent all pain he kept locked in throughout that time, he couldn't talk about it all simply because he had no one until he met Hunter, she understood him and never saw him as evil, she wanted to bring out the best in him which she did, the two would eventually become a couple retiring from street fighting which then lead to Zach becoming a merc for hire. These are but a few of the great and memorable lines that pervades Christopher Nolan's pulp masterpiece The Dark Knight. I mean, Nolan's film is not only an amazing superhero blockbuster film, but it's also an amazing film, period. It so beautifully manages to be deft in its thematic complexity and seamless in its marriage of substance and style, it's no joke. The Dark Knight still holds up eleven years after its release and will continue to hold up in the years to come. First, The Dark Knight is beautiful and superlative as a film because of the various parts that mesh together: the consummate direction by Christopher Nolan, the masterful and first-rate writing from Chris and Jonathan Nolan, the proficient editing of Lee Smith that manages to move this 153-minute film at a fast yet fluid and coherent pace, the sharp and powerful action that packs a mighty punch, and the bombastic music of Hans Zimmer that is just so memorable and, well, epic. Second, The Dark Knight would not be such a great film without the acting, and boy is the acting fantastic. Christian Bale, reprising his role from Batman Begins, just nails down the roles of Bruce Wayne and Batman, going on to become the definitive cinematic Batman. Gary Oldman and Michael Caine likewise give amazing performances, and so do Maggie Gyllenhall and Aaron Eckhart as Rachel Dawes and Harvey Dent/Two Face. Likewise, Eckhart's Two-Face is one of the most skillfully displayed characters not only in superhero cinema but in cinema, period. But the real show-stealer, who gives near-perfect chemistry with Bale's Batman is Heath Ledger as the Joker. Everything about Ledger's performance is just flawless. The menacing voice, the devilish mannerism, the demonic persona, the depth that comes from Ledger and from the Nolan brothers' writing, all these are but a glimpse of what makes Ledger's Joker so brilliant.

Nightwing #59 (2019)
There‚Äôs a new team in town who will have to learn the hard way that fighting injustice doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôre cut out to be a superhero. As the newly formed Nightwings are forced to deal with a fiery threat they never saw coming, reluctant recruit Ric Grayson has to make the choice between a carefree life without capes or answering the call that‚Äôs been ringing his entire life‚Äîthe call to be a hero. Join Ric Grayson and the Nightwings as they learn what it takes to be a team‚Äîand what happens when you fight who you truly are.

The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King
When I hear the word "epic" Return of the King always comes to mind. When I first watched this whole trilogy; after I had watched Fellowship and Towers I really didn't think this film could stick the landing. After all, it's kind of rare for a third chapter of a trilogy to be this good. But oh how wrong I was. And how glad I am that I was.
This film is an absolute masterpiece on every front. From it's story telling, to it's characters, to it's great special effects, to it's jaw dropping action sequences and literally everything else in this movie, Return of the King is perfect.
And truthfully I don't know where to begin when reviewing this film. Everything is just so easy to praise. This film has some of my favorite moments in not just the Lord of the Rings trilogy, but of film in general. Who could forget amazing scenes like The Ride of the Rohirrim, or Sam vs Shelob? Or what about The Battle of Minas Tirith? In all seriousness that is without a doubt the greatest battle ever put to screen. Everytime I watch it I get so many chills and goosebumps. Every time I sit on the edge of my seat. Despite knowing the outcome, my heart pounds out of anxiousness for these character's fates. And then the ending. Or endingS, if you prefer. The way the ending wraps up the trilogy in such a bittersweet way is just perfect.
And overall I honestly would put this in the top 10 films of all time. It is without a doubt one of the greatest films ever made that concluded one of the greatest trilogies ever made so perfectly. Which is why I'm giving The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King a 10/10

ROUND 1 OF THE DIRECTORS TOURNAMENT:
______________________________________
Akira Kurosawa vs Martin Scorsese ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
(Comment below who you think is the better director, or your personal preference of the two... If you give me an explanation on why you voted who you did, then I‚Äôll count your vote as 2 points.)

Here's the next one, and probably my favourite foreign film of all time. 
Seven Samurai is not only my favourite foreign film, but one of my favourite films. Period. 
What Kurosawa made back in 1954, to this day, is no less than incredible. He not just changed action movies, he created a way to shoot and show action that revolutionized the genre and are seen to this day. I think every modern director should be forced to watch this before they make a new action flick. Get inspired, reminded of a way to shoot action that actually feels real, and gritty, and, most importantly, shows the consequences of said action. 
When is the last time you saw a big action scene and actually felt it? Felt the importance of the scene, felt the significance of people dying? 
Kurosawa mixes the drama and emotions with some greatly shot action scenes. You see the bandits die. You see death. You count as all the bandits fall, one by one. 
Instead of just focusing on the hero(es) of the story bringing mayhem to the evil bad guys, you focus on the consequences of said heroes‚Äô actions. And it creates a better film by doing it. 
I really wish that more modern action movies would do this to at least some degree. Make us experience the emotions behind the action, the drama of it. And not just show us some guy with superhuman strength beating an inexhaustible amount of crooks and baddies.

Denger nama Akira Kurosawa yang terlintas di pikiran, sudah pasti Jepang, depth, socio-culturalnya, blockingnya, proporsi gambarnya, komposisi dan gayanya yang teatrikal. Itu semua ada di hampir setiap film nya dan sama-sama menghasilkan sebuah sajian yang , ‚ÄúEpik!‚Äù.
‚Ä¢
Epik menurut Kurosawa bagaimana sih? Apa epik itu harus yang bener-bener sebuah aksi yang wah, memukau gitu? (sempit!!!) Tidak untuk Kurosawa. Kurosawa memperkenalkan ‚Äúepik‚Äù dalam kesederhanaannya dalam blocking, editing yang bisa dibilang jadi turun temurun ke film-film yang banyak kalian lihat, seperti filmnya Spielberg, Francis Ford Coppola, ataupun Sergio Leone dalam filmnya A Fistful of Dollars sebagai contohnya. Kurosawa yang master dalam mengembangkan trademark dalam sinematik telah menjadi inspirasi dalam menerapkan ataupun menginovasikan tapi tak ada yang meragukan betapa timeless elemen-elemen yang disodorkan di dalam karyanya, otentiknya dalam merevisi elemen simematik tradisional dan membuatnya dalam sebuah karya utuh yang spesial dan modern.
‚Ä¢
Biasanya, sutradara ditengah proses ada yang namanya proses mencari sebuah tone, gaya dalam bercerita namun disini, Kurosawa menemukan kemampuan impresifnya dalam film Sanshiro Sugata (1943) yang unggul dan menarik perhatian kala itu. Tentang judo saga, menggabungkan martial arts dengan bagaimana sih identitas Jepang dulu dengan filosofi dari judo itu sendiri. Ditampilkan dalam tone yang puitis, halus meski intensitas tergambar di dalamnya, Kurosawa menunjukkan axial cutnya yang begitu menarik disini. Film debut dan juga film propaganda ini menunjukkan camera work-nya yang impresif dalam menangkap detil-detil objek dan menatanya dalam gambar dan menekankan ekspresi karakter melalui axial cut tanpa perlu menunjukkan reaksi close-up sang karakter.
‚Ä¢

Throwback Thursday review (1 of 2)- 4/5 ‚≠êÔ∏è- ‚ÄúPrince of The City‚Äù is the 80s police corruption classic by the legendary Sidney Lumet who previously tackled police corruption in the Al Pacino clastic ‚ÄúSerpico‚Äù. The film follows New York police officer Daniel Ciello (Treat Williams) who is not a perfect cop. When Rick Cappalino (Norman Parker) from the U.S. Justice Department approaches him with a personal request to investigate police corruption, Ciello agrees provided he is not forced to turn in his fellow crooked cops. But as he delves deeper into the underbelly of drug crime, he realizes that it may be impossible to keep his promises as he he soon discovers that he's in over his head, and nobody can be trusted. Like he did with ‚ÄúSerpico‚Äù, Lumet captures the grittiness and ugliness of New York with a clear and masterful eye. The film is 2 hours and 40 minutes long so it is a long watch but a worthy one, with an incredibly detailed script which isn‚Äôt shocking as Lumet was known to do a lot of research for his projects. Proof of how authentic and great his search was, the head of the Drug Enforcement Administration called Lumet for a copy of the movie for the DEA training program. As much as I love the film I will say that he does tend to glamorize corrupt cops a bit more than any normal filmmaker should and that can be a hit and miss with the audience depending on the person. It does have deep meanings however showing how difficult it is for Daniel to stick to a straight path in a crooked world without hurting those that he loves.

Treat Williams gives a dynamite performance as Daniel; portraying a conflicted man with so much assuredness, it‚Äôs incredible to think he didn‚Äôt become a bigger star based off this movie. Like Pacino in ‚ÄúSerpico‚Äù we see him trying to figure out what to do regarding close friends but make no mistake; unlike Serpico, Daniel is as dirty as they come. At the beginning of the film, the cameras are all positioned above eye level and mounted with wide-angle lenses to give the appearance of greater distance between the subjects. My favorites:

One Flew Over the Cuckoo‚Äôs Nest:  I read this in my 10th grade English Honors class with Mrs. Dellano. She was young and passionate and is reason I was an English teacher.  This book, in particular, she had a real passion for. It was the first time I read anything like it and I could not believe all the symbolism and deeper meaning. I relate to R.P. McMurphy in many ways. It gave me a love for literature and led me done the Beatnik road.

A New Earth: I first read this because Oprah recommended it.  I read it around 2005 and it changed my life. I couldn‚Äôt believe what he was saying and for the first time in my life I felt mindfulness was attainable. 
A Course in Miracles: I have not read it in total yet, but every day that I read it I feel further transformed. 
You are a Badass:  I have read more self-help books than I can count, but this one is different. Sincero‚Äôs humor gets you through the tough times and each time I read it, I walk away with something new. 
Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows ü§ì‚ö°Ô∏è: I think Jospeh Campbell would approve of this modern myth. I love the whole series but this book has so many deeper spiritual lessons that bring me to tears no matter how many times I have read it.

üëâ It was the final film of Leone's career and the first feature film he had directed in 13 years. The cinematography was by¬†Tonino Delli Colli, and the film score by¬†Ennio Morricone üëë  Sergio Leone originally envisaged two three-hour films, then a single 269-minute version, but was convinced by distributors to shorten it to 229 minutes. The American distributors,¬†The Ladd Company, further shortened it to 139 minutes, and rearranged the scenes into chronological order, without Leone's involvement. The shortened version was a critical and commercial flop in the United States, and critics who had seen both versions harshly condemned the changes that were made. The original "European cut" has remained a critical favorite and frequently appears in lists of the greatest¬†gangster films of all time.

Day 108 is one my favorite foreign language movie ever. It‚Äôs the 1998 movie ‚ÄúCinema Paradiso‚Äù that has Philippe Noiret and Jacques Perrin.  Directed by 5+/5.  It tells the story about a filmmaker Salvatore Di Vita who had to return to his village after an old friend die.  While there he remembers his childhood when falling in love with the pictures at the cinema of his home village.  Salvatore forms a deep friendship with the cinema's projectionist Alfredo.  In time he becomes the projectionist after an accident involves Alfredo.  Alfredo tells Salvatore to leave his small town and pursue his passion for filmmaking.  Jacques Perrin is Salvatore and Philippe Noiret is Alfredo.  I love this movie so much.  I seen this movie over hundred times and I still enjoy it.  The last scene always brings a tear in my eyes. Episode review for Black Mirror: White Christmas.

So, we're at the end of my Black Mirror reviews. Which means I can go watch season 3 now. Before seeing White Christmas, my favourite episode was White Bear. I can't even explain to you the look on my face and the feeling inside me after I watched this episode. It is the kind of episode that some may not like because it doesn't hit you in the head as hard as some other episodes do. Because my opinion is that this episode takes a personal taste. But it's my favourite for many reasons. As I said, it isn't as brutal as the others with its message. But in a way, it really is. Because it's story is a lot more personal. And whichever person you relate to in the tale the most, it does give you a rough story and a harsh reality for the kind of person you will be in situations such as this. I'm not going to give away too much about the plot because I think it's the kind of thing you should just go in blind with and have no knowledge of what might happen. Now before I get really into the story and writing, I want to talk about the performances. I have to straight up say that without Jon Hamm and Rafe Spall, this episode would not have been nearly as effective as it was. With Jon Hamm, he creates this character that I completely bought. One that was so natural and at times cocky and unappreciative but also had a strong backstory and a reason for the kind of person he is. What I thought was great about his character was that he was inappropriately funny sometimes, and cracked jokes that seemed to always bring a smile to my face even in times of drama. And it wasn't comedy that was overdone like The Waldo Moment was. It was effective and had meaning to it. He is a character that I see as sort of being an antihero. A creepy, unsettling character but one with some real heart underneath. I think Jon Hamm was fantastic and it's the best I've ever seen him perform. That being said, I still need to go watch Mad Men soon. (CONTINUED IN COMMENTS)

The whole story of technology and being able to block people in real life like you do on social media was inspired as were the twist to this amazing episode! THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UGLY (1966) This movie is ‚Äòthe big one‚Äô in the trilogy. You don‚Äôt have to be a western fan to enjoy it. Chronologically it comes behind both the previously filmed movies, takes place during the civil war. Also unlike the previous 2 movies it is filmed in the states. What I really love about this movie is the kill count. The good kills the most people, the ugly is 2nd in kill count, and the bad kills the least of all. Despite the kill count, we are convinced throughout the movie that the good is good, the ugly is ugly (not by looks, but by soul) and the bad is bad. ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~The good, or Blondie, played by Clint Eastwood, isn‚Äôt necessarily too good, in the traditional sense, although, in the end he ends up doing the right thing. In this movie we also find out about the origin of his iconic poncho. ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~Eli Wallach does a terrific job at playing Tuco (the ugly). The character is iconic, and it is said that Eli improvised some of the scenes. The ugly constantly shifts through moods depending on the situation he‚Äôs in, he is cunning. ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~The bad, played by Lee Van Cleef, is a dislikable character from the start. He has ideals, but bad ones and alters them to his own use. In the beginning we see how he takes a man‚Äôs money and than he kills him. He then proceeds to kill his boss in a way to justify why he took the man‚Äôs money. #thegoodthebadandtheugly #clinteastwood #eliwallach #leevancleef #spaghettiwestern #review #sergioleone #enniomorricone #movie #movies #cowboy #screen #bigscreen #film #filmography #cinematography #cinema #western #poncho

In Elio Petri's riveting crime drama a highly regarded Italian police inspector murders his mistress, only to become part of the homicide investigation that follows. The inspector proceeds to plant clues at the crime scene as his fellow officers either ignore or fail to recognize his obvious tampering. But all is not as it seems. While the killer may have an inside track on fabricating his own innocence, he also seems to be testing the competence and integrity of Italian law enforcement.

Salah 1 cuplikan yang paling ane suka, saat Charlie Chaplin yang berperan sebagai Adenoid Hynkel (plesetan dari Adolf Hitler) berpidato di film¬†The Great Dictator. Film ini¬†merupakan film parodi yang memang berkelas.

Film berdurasi 124 menit yang dibuat satu tahun sebelum tentara Amerika Serikat mengikuti Perang Dunia Kedua ini seakan-akan mampu memberikan dampak propaganda kepada pemerintah AS untuk segera bergerak melawan Nazi Jerman. Film komedi drama ini adalah¬†satire¬†bagi Nazi Jerman yang ingin menguasai dunia dengan cara brutal. Sehingga pesan yang ingin disampaikan jelas: perdamaian. Akhir dalam film menegaskan hal itu. Pertukaran posisi antara si tukang cukur dan si diktator menjadi inti cerita dari¬†The Great Dictator, bahwa diktator yang besar bukanlah diktator yang angkuh, kaku, kejam, penuh kebencian, dan tidak toleran. Diktator yang ‚Äúbesar‚Äù dalam artian memilih untuk menghentikan perang, memberi kebebasan bagi individu, berperikemanusiaan, dan menyatukan umat manusia dalam persaudaraan. The first clown of cinema and one of the earliest masters of the medium, Charlie Chaplin was born 130 years ago today.
From the music halls of England through to The Tramp, his wild successes of the silent era to his revered and courageous satire, ‚ÄòThe Great Dictator‚Äô, Chaplin‚Äòs combination of slapstick comedy and heartfelt pathos proved visionary.
In the public eye for three quarters of a century, there were moments of ostracisation and controversy, as well as revival. 
Receiving an Honorary Academy Award in 1972, Chaplin was given a twelve minute standing ovation - the longest in Oscars history.

This was made while watching princess mononoke. It comes with a short poem: ‚ÄúWhen I was born, a curse was woven into my fate
One that impedes my ability for love
And feeds a desire 
for destruction and hate

I have found many ways to inflict pain unto myself in the few short years of my life
Several being starvation, greed, 
and the edge of a knife

Loved ones are banished
Door are locked
Aching stomachs are famished
All communication is blocked

Today, still waters became a bubbling surface
With a pop, it expelled its vile stench
Exposing its purpose
Without fear and doubt how does one expect to succeed
A dull pain may persist 
But old wounds no longer bleed‚Äù

I've been reading a short Easter devotional this week. And one of the days it referenced the scene in the Easter story where the Jesus takes Peter, James, and John to the garden of Gethsemane with him to pray right before Judas shows up with an army to take Jesus to his trial. Jesus asks the 3 disciples to pray with him as he was in agony. Instead they slept. The writer posed the question how different would our lives and even our world be if we prayed instead of spiritually sleeping. He used the example of watching TV or reading novels while there's so much pain and loneliness and sin to be prayed for. He says "we snore while our culture crumbles"‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
This Easter season I challenge myself and all of us to not be caught sleeping when Jesus calls us to pray for Him.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

Psalm 87 üíï
God chose and loves the city of Jerusalem (Zion), as He chose and loves His people. Jerusalem is Gods city, the city of the ‚ÄòGreat King‚Äô (Psalm 48:2). But the psalmist notes that many other nations are now coming to worship God in Jerusalem (v4-5). The psalmist is also conscious of the privilege of being born in Gods city and being recorded in His book (v6).
Two problems came from this exalted view of the city. First, the reality did not match the ideal. For the majority of Israels history Jerusalem was characterised by failed leadership, violence, and fear. 
The second problem was complacency and presumption. The people came to regard the mere presence of the temple in the city as a guarantee of Gods protection (Jet 4:7). The prophets warned them about this but the people wouldn‚Äôt listen. So Jerusalem was destroyed in 587 BC and again in 70 AD. Even the son of God was rejected and crucified when he came to his own city!
So when we read this passage we need to read beyond the stone and mortar of Jerusalem in the centuries before Christ. We can look forward to the ‚Äònew Jerusalem‚Äô the centrepiece of the new heaven and new earth which God will create when the world finally ends. And remember for those of us who know and love Christ, our citizenship is in Heaven! üíï #psalms #psalm87 #zion #cityofGod #jerusalem #joy #foundation #citizenship #fountainsofjoy #blessed

I'm trying to erase this phrase from my vocabulary. I often find myself thinking I deserve an award, recognition, a treat for successes and accomplishments and working hard. Harvey Weinstein interested to adapt One Hundred Years of Solitude met with Marquez to discuss matters regarding film rights and direction and at first Marquez agreed. He told Weinstein that if he, and director Giuseppe Tornatore, wanted the rights to¬†One Hundred Years of Solitude¬†they were the men for the job. But there was one catch: "We must film the entire book, but only release one chapter ‚Äì two minutes long ‚Äì each year, for 100 years," Weinstein said.

This is the reason why there is no film adaptation to this book. Universally hailed as a major work of literature, no film has ever been made of the book, as the author declined every invitation to sign away the film rights.

As a person I am not someone who looks forward to film adaptations of books. Almost always I am disappointed and therefore often refuse to watch on screen the books that I read. However, I like parallels (I am sure that isn't difficult to guess considering that is all I do with my Instagram) and while reading Marquez I came upon exact parallels for Colonel Aureliano Buend√≠a and Jos√© Arcadio. What's more in the film they too are brothers.

To be honest, I feel Matteo is Colonel Aureliano Buend√≠a in every way. While Nicola is Jos√© Arcadio when he goes off with the gypsies.

For the longest time I wanted to share this understanding with someone. But who would understand what I'm trying to say? Hopefully someone who has both seen the film and read the book will get what I'm trying to express. Nonetheless I will make my point explicit in my following posts.

Top Next Generation and Top Key Players of K-Movie Industry

This year is a meaningful year for the movie industry, the 100th anniversary of Korean movies.¬†K-movies, Korean actors and directors who have grown rapidly over a period of 100 years are recognized on the world stage. Sports Seoul conducted questionnaires to 100 experts including content creators, planners, producers, public relations and marketing in the field of entertainment industry such as broadcasting, movies, and musics from the 25th to 31st of last month to know who are the Key Players of K-Movie Industry and its Next Generation.

5. #JooJiHoon (10 votes)

1. #LeeByungHun (46 votes)
2. #ParkChanWook (16 votes)

4. #BaeDooNa (14 votes)

Denger nama Akira Kurosawa yang terlintas di pikiran, sudah pasti Jepang, depth, socio-culturalnya, blockingnya, proporsi gambarnya, komposisi dan gayanya yang teatrikal. Itu semua ada di hampir setiap film nya dan sama-sama menghasilkan sebuah sajian yang , ‚ÄúEpik!‚Äù.
‚Ä¢
Epik menurut Kurosawa bagaimana sih? Apa epik itu harus yang bener-bener sebuah aksi yang wah, memukau gitu? (sempit!!!) Tidak untuk Kurosawa. Kurosawa memperkenalkan ‚Äúepik‚Äù dalam kesederhanaannya dalam blocking, editing yang bisa dibilang jadi turun temurun ke film-film yang banyak kalian lihat, seperti filmnya Spielberg, Francis Ford Coppola, ataupun Sergio Leone dalam filmnya A Fistful of Dollars sebagai contohnya. Kurosawa yang master dalam mengembangkan trademark dalam sinematik telah menjadi inspirasi dalam menerapkan ataupun menginovasikan tapi tak ada yang meragukan betapa timeless elemen-elemen yang disodorkan di dalam karyanya, otentiknya dalam merevisi elemen simematik tradisional dan membuatnya dalam sebuah karya utuh yang spesial dan modern.
‚Ä¢
Biasanya, sutradara ditengah proses ada yang namanya proses mencari sebuah tone, gaya dalam bercerita namun disini, Kurosawa menemukan kemampuan impresifnya dalam film Sanshiro Sugata (1943) yang unggul dan menarik perhatian kala itu. Tentang judo saga, menggabungkan martial arts dengan bagaimana sih identitas Jepang dulu dengan filosofi dari judo itu sendiri. Ditampilkan dalam tone yang puitis, halus meski intensitas tergambar di dalamnya, Kurosawa menunjukkan axial cutnya yang begitu menarik disini. Film debut dan juga film propaganda ini menunjukkan camera work-nya yang impresif dalam menangkap detil-detil objek dan menatanya dalam gambar dan menekankan ekspresi karakter melalui axial cut tanpa perlu menunjukkan reaksi close-up sang karakter.

Paths of glory provides one of the most emotional and powerful endings for me.The savagery of war has affected these men psychologically and emotionally.The war deranged them.These men were of course not the same as they used to be.When the girl was intoduced,these men look at her as a war trophy.They just want to drink and escape from reality through her.But when she sings,even without understanding the words,all of them were reminded of their humanity again.These soldiers were reminded of their family,and who they were fighting for at the first place.It reminded us that war may temporarily deprive these soldier's senses or humanity.But those virtues are still somewhere down there.Kubrick crafted a perfect ending.

Lonely are the Brave (1962)

Kirk Douglas is one of my favorites to watch on screen. All of his greatest characters possess a great drive within them based off their own individual moral systems; Colonel Dax in ‚ÄòPaths of Glory‚Äô fighting against systematic corruption in the military hierarchy system, the titular hero in ‚ÄòSpartacus‚Äô leading a slave revolt against the Roman repression, even as the pseudo-journalist Chuck Tatum trying to milk a story only for his own gain in ‚ÄòAce in the Hole‚Äô, he still is guided only by his morals. 
This is why no other actor was to play cowboy Jack Burns, a rugged individualist guided by no one, the type of man that built America into what it is, a man from another time. Traveling by horse in the modern world (at that time the 1950‚Äôs) his pony struggles to cross streets on account of the cars whizzing past, a metaphor for Banks and his chances in the modern world?
The movie ultimately becomes a chase to the border after Burns breaks out of jail, after intentionally going in so he could break out his partner in crime, only for his partner to decline. (Another signifier of the cowboy‚Äôs fading ways). He must evade the police, equipped with modern technologies.

The sheriff that gives chase is played by the wonderful Walter Matthau, an actor who has made his money by playing good intentioned people usually of the slovenly variety. He sympathizers with Burns, noting that all of his infractions were based off revolt of the system or plain patriotism on certain days like February 22 (George Washington‚Äôs birthday) or June 14 (Flag Day). He knows Burns is a relic that stands for something long gone,  and he even semi roots for him to escape successfully. 
What culminates is a crashing of worlds, the dying past and the ever coming present, the ways of the cowboys and that of modern America. Kirk Douglas is still alive today, at 102, and he too, just like his character is the last string of a time before, the last great actor of the golden age of Hollywood, carrying what he represents to the very end.

Directed by David Miller

There's room yet, so maybe others can include their names as well some day!

‚Ä¢
It's not me
But for who I am
A good man
I stand rejected
I don't know what to do about it
But to remain standing
And be it alone
All on my own
To stand up
For who I know I am
‚Ä¢

Note: I cannot live up, or more accurately, live down to other people's projections of who I am not. It's impossible. I am not some actor on a stage, who can play a role in another's melodrama. I cannot sit down, to suit the fallacy of who other's need me to be, to suit their fantasy.

Invariably, to suit themselves
Everyone turns their back
The thing is
Whether one recognizes it or not
We are not inanimate
We are intimate
We all have a heart
We are more than just...
An old battered alley cat
A lost pixel on your navsat
A place to hang your dirty hat
Or an out worn welcome door mat
We are more than you can imagine
And so much more than that
So recognize this
When you make your 180¬∞ turn
There'll be no counter attack
Nor anyone left behind, to turn back

To be honest, if it weren‚Äôt for meeting @jqueue__ I don‚Äôt think I would have started animating as early as I‚Äôm doing now. I think he was the push needed to get this show on the run. In a way, I guess you can say he pushed me out of my box, and I hope I helped him along the way too. 
I started this in June 2018 and finished it September that same year. 
While JQueue has probably moved on from it, I‚Äôm just now stepping out my box and trying to embrace my future. No time to be sitting around feeling sad. 
Out of the Box, to me, is a means of escape of what we tell each other what we‚Äôre supposed to be when we could just be ourselves. It does no one any good to be kept to such a standard and suppress what we mean to ourselves. When we step out our box, we step out beyond the world to live a life we‚Äôre meant to live. Each and every one of us.

And the crashing of the sea

But in the grey of the morning
My mind becomes confused
Between the dead and the sleeping
And the road that I must choose

Note: So many years ago, yet at the same time, just yesterday and now today, these timeless words from an old scratched record album, left behind by my long lost sister, spoke to my soul of things forgotten, yet to know. #valeriemasters #stolenyoursoul #poetry #poet #playwright #writers #bloggersofinstagram #poetslife #poetsandwriters #wordlover #wordgasm #heartofpoets #herheartpoetry #bookcommunity #bookobsessed #wordobsession #deadpoetssociety #breathout

Cold places and empty spaces 
Quiet corners and emotional loners
the corridors of the mind
Guiding the passage of time
The essence of air
To be found inevitably
Hidden an the open somewhere
Dark secrets to be kept
Truths left slept
To be the last on Earth
To escape all the hurt 
Once again into abyss
Hide and seek is what I seek
Our shadows appearing 
on the walls
Kept company by the rubble
Created from when the pillars 
Made out of our dreams 
That eventually did fall

To my son,

Know that being your mom is both a noun and a verb.  As your mom I will protect you through this world until you are strong enough to let me go.  Never be afraid to hold your head up and stay true to your values. Avoid the crowd and make your own path as I made mine.  Do what truly makes you happy and don't worry about validation from others. I can only hope that someone wants me here for a long time to watch you grow. I love you so much and will hold your hand and never let it go.

Love,
Your Mom
